Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis Consensus guidelines Molecular mimicry Inflammatory cascade Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM) typically occurs after a viral infection or recent vaccination. ADEM can represent a diagnostic challenge for clinicians, as many disorders (inflammatory and noninflammatory) have a similar clinical and radiologic presentation. The differential diagnosis for multifocal hyperintense lesions on neuroimaging includes an exhaustive list of potential mimickers, namely infectious, inflammatory, rheumatologic, metabolic, nutritional, and degenerative entities. 